I am formally requesting Atlassian adoption of the Metadata plugin. This plugin provides critical functionality that frankly should have been  part of Confluence. Looking at communications from Atlassian staff, it's clear you guys recognize this module's usefulness.

Per http://developer.atlassian.com/jira/browse/META-107, the Metadata plugin is basically unsupported even though it has 81 issues going back 3 years.

Even the CMS Watch found fault with your maintenance of the Metadata module in its 2009 _The Enterprise Social Software & Collaboration Report_: "several [important] plugins remain unsupported... . For example, the popular Metadata plugin ... is not supported officially, so you might find yourself in a tough spot if the original developer decides to work on something else."

To reproduce: Create a panel macro with contents that has macros (e.g. \{toc}, \{userlister}) inlined with other contents, for instance:

{noformat}
{panel}
My line {info}here{info}
{panel}
{noformat}

See [screenshot|^panel.jpg] for the result.

Workaround: Create a new line for the macro, for instance:

{noformat}
{panel}
My line 
{info}here{info}
{panel}
{noformat}

This problem is _not reproducible_ in Confluence 2.8.2, 2.10.1

h3. Problem

Confluence doesn't feel modern, while some of its competitors are ahead in this regard.

h3. Fix

Small visual improvements over time can slowly make Confluence contemporary. One such fix is to put a subtle gradient and shadow onto the Confluence header like so:

!design.png|thumbnail!

!design_with_menu.png|thumbnail!

This will also require the header to be made 29px high.

Quick code solution by Chris Broadfoot:

{code}
#poweredby {
	padding-top: 10px !important;
}

#header {
    background-image: url(http://extranet.atlassian.com/download/attachments/673088317/gradient-header.gif);
    background-position: bottom;
}

#main {
	border-top: none !important;
	padding: 10px !important;
	margin-left: -10px !important;
	margin-right: -10px !important;
	background: white url(http://www.ibm.com/i/v16/t/sprites-t1.gif) repeat-x scroll 0 -814px;
}
{code}

h3. Reason for severity

The header is everywhere.

